AGI - "It is not sure that 2025 is a turning year for the conflict in Ukraine: US President, Donald Trump, is in a hurry to close, but negotiations with the Russians have not yet entered into live >" and we must wait to understand what will be the fall point of the necessary compromises that all parties will have to do. It is the analysis of the former Italian ambassador in Kiev, Pier Francesco Zazo, who gave the AGI an interview on the third anniversary of the Russian invasion of Ukraine, in which it outlines the possible developments of the situation in light of the direct dialogue Moscow-Washington and the 180-degree turn of the Republican administration on support in Kiev. Zazo - who was in the Ukrainian capital on the first day of Russian aggression and remained there until last summer - has an experience also in the diplomatic headquarters of Moscow; in this "delicate phase" the next key step will be to see what it defines as "Capestro" > between the US and Ukraine on the joint exploitation of rare lands.
&nbsp;
An understanding that, just today the deputy first ministra for the European and Euro-Atlantic integration of Ukraine, Olga Stefanishyna, reportedly lies in its "final phase". Trump, "does not have an articulated plan for peace in Ukraine, but wants to quickly conclude an agreement" with Russian counterpart Vladimir Putin, presumably since he considers China the true systemic opponent of the United States. "To decide for the end of the war, however, will be more Putin than Trump: the leader of the Kremlin understands only the language of force, does not rush unlike the American president and only when he feels he is no longer able to win or obtain additional territorial gains and concessions from Trump could accept a compromise," Zazo explains.
&nbsp;
"Trump" analyzes the former ambassador, "on the one hand he is available to make concessions in Moscow, so that Putin is convinced to accept the truce and on the other he exerts a strong pressure on the weakest part, Ukraine>, threatening the possible suspension of the indispensable military aid". US President, "also pursues a business approach, where he presses President Volodymyr Zelensky to sign an agreement on joint exploitation of rare land as a refund for data aid."
&nbsp;
"It remains, however, still to be checked if in exchange for the signing of the agreement by Zelensky, the Unti States are available to provide credible security guarantees and give military aid," Zazo warns. "If so, Americans would also have an economic interest in asking Putin to accept a truce on the current line of the forehead, much more than most rare lands are in the territories under Russian control."
&nbsp;
"For Ukraine, the risk of American distrust > from the conflict threatened by Trump is real; therefore, in this difficult phase calls for the support of European allies", the diplomat continues, outlining how "more credible scenario" that in which Kiev receives adequate military aid from the allies to strengthen its ability to deterrence and prevent future aggression and the sending of adequate international peacekeeping forces once the truce is signed".
&nbsp;
It would be a question of applying the so-called "porcospino model", he said, "like that of Israel and South Korea, which have modern armed forces and great self-defense skills, although not members of the Atlantic Alliance". For its part, Moscow still has not declared that concessions is ready to do but it is clear that "the objective of the Kremlin remains unchanged>: bring Ukraine back under Russian control by realizing Putin's messianic and revanchist dream of recreating an empire and returning to Russia the status of world-wide eurasian power." Zazo recalls that in this perspective the existence of an independent Ukrainian state is not conceivable for Putin, "convinced supporter of the fundamentalist myth of the 'Russian world', according to which the Russians and Ukrainians are a single people".
&nbsp;
"It is necessary to understand whether Washington will yield or not to Putin's further demands, which cannot be satisfied with a ceasefire along the current line of the front, but it wants in full the four regions annexed in 2023 and could insist on the demilitarization of Ukraine in order to recover its control."
&nbsp;
"The Ukrainians are now resigned to the fact that they will not enter NATO >", admits the former ambassador on the day when also the US National Security Councilman, Michael Waltz, reiterated that the Kiev accession to NATO "is not on the table". In Kiev "they are ready to accept the loss of the occupied territories, but they will insist on asking credible American security guarantees at least in the form of military aid."
&nbsp;
"If they do not get them, they will continue to fight by trusting on the help of Europeans and knowing that they have no alternative because they do not trust Putin's regime." According to the former ambassador, "the Ukrainians will never accept a possible dismilitarization because it would certify the unconditional surrender of the country".
&nbsp;
"The most credible route to arrive hopefully to a truce that would still be fragile", the diplomat concludes, "would be the one based on the achievement of a compromise: Moscow should settle for the already occupied territories and its veto at the entrance to NATO, but Ukraine should at least receive adequate military aid from Western allies to strengthen its capacity for military deterrence." &nbsp;

